🔥 Core concepts every DevOps engineer should understand
✅ Each Pod gets its own IP
Kubernetes follows a flat networking model where pods can communicate across nodes without NAT (depending on the CNI implementation).
✅ CNI is not built into Kubernetes
You must install a CNI plugin such as:
Calico (supports Network Policies and scalability)
Flannel (simple and easy to set up)
Cilium (advanced networking using eBPF)
Each plugin has different trade-offs in terms of performance, features, and complexity.

⚡ Practical debugging perspective
When troubleshooting Kubernetes issues, networking should be one of the first things to check:
Pods unable to communicate → Verify CNI configuration
Services not reachable → Check kube-proxy and networking rules
DNS issues → Validate CoreDNS and network paths
Cross-node communication issues → Inspect overlay networking
Many Kubernetes issues that appear complex are often related to networking.
⚙️ How CNI works (simplified)
A pod is scheduled to a node
Kubelet invokes the CNI plugin
The plugin assigns an IP address
Network interfaces and routes are configured
The pod becomes reachable within the cluster
💭 Pro Tip
Always validate pod networking early:
kubectl get pods -o wide
Review pod IPs and node distribution—this often helps identify networking issues quickly.
Understanding Kubernetes networking is essential for building reliable systems—not optional.
